TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Beta-logistic Model for the Analysis of Sequential Labor Force Participation by Married Women
AU  - Heckman, James J.
AU  - Willis, Robert J.
Y1  - 1977/02/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260544
DO  - 10.1086/260544
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 27
EP  - 58
VL  - 85
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In this paper, we discuss statistical problems that arise in studying sequences of quantal responses (e.g., labor force participation) in panel data on heterogeneous populations (i.e., populations in which there is unobserved variation in response probabilities). Assuming that response probabilities are governed by a beta distribution, we derive a generalization on of the cross-section logit model to enable it to deal with sequences of discrete events in panel data. This model is applied to panel data on labor force participation of married women. One of our findings is that the distribution of participation probabilities is U shaped, indicating that most women have participation probabilities near zero or near one.
AB  - In this paper, we discuss statistical problems that arise in studying sequences of quantal responses (e.g., labor force participation) in panel data on heterogeneous populations (i.e., populations in which there is unobserved variation in response probabilities). Assuming that response probabilities are governed by a beta distribution, we derive a generalization on of the cross-section logit model to enable it to deal with sequences of discrete events in panel data. This model is applied to panel data on labor force participation of married women. One of our findings is that the distribution of participation probabilities is U shaped, indicating that most women have participation probabilities near zero or near one.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260544
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260544
Y2  - 2024/03/22
