TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Theory of the Size and Shape of Nations
AU  - Friedman, David
Y1  - 1977/02/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260545
DO  - 10.1086/260545
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 59
EP  - 77
VL  - 85
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - If territory goes to the nation which values it most as a source of revenue, nations will be shaped to maximize joint revenue, net of collection costs. Trade, as a major potential revenue source, should imply large nations; rent should imply small nations; and labor should imply that nations will have closed boundaries or be culturally homogeneous (to maximize exit costs). I show how this fits the pattern of European experience from Roman times to the present. Results of preliminary numerical tests of predictions of the theory are given.
AB  - If territory goes to the nation which values it most as a source of revenue, nations will be shaped to maximize joint revenue, net of collection costs. Trade, as a major potential revenue source, should imply large nations; rent should imply small nations; and labor should imply that nations will have closed boundaries or be culturally homogeneous (to maximize exit costs). I show how this fits the pattern of European experience from Roman times to the present. Results of preliminary numerical tests of predictions of the theory are given.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260545
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260545
Y2  - 2024/03/22
